column11: With 238 proposals submitted from 54 different states/provinces (Amazon, World Time Zones), Amazon has said a selection for its second headquarters will be made in early 2018. News surrounding the possible location changes weekly Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

This forecast is based off of three factors. First, because Amazon has been searching for its second headquarters for more than a year, it is logical to conclude that Amazon will hold a press conference to announce this decision. The concluding time for this challenge question is 2:59 AM EST on 1 October 2018, approximately two hours from now. Therefore, it is unlikely that Amazon will have a press conference to announce their decision, while their audience would be substantially suboptimal, within the next two hours.﻿ Second, reports have been published that Amazon officials visited a Chicago bid location in late August, alluding to the fact that the selection process is ongoing (https://www.businessinsider.com/amazon-hq2-reps-visited-chicago-second-time-report-2018-9). These officials' trip to the Chicago location is notable, as " it could mean the contest is far from over, and it may be more-open than had previously been speculated." (https://www.businessinsider.com/amazon-hq2-reps-visited-chicago-second-time-report-2018-9). Lastly, Amazon officials have asserted that they will make their decision by the end of the year and strategically it would be the most logical to wait to select a city until after the 2018 elections, as Amazon will seek to ensure that the deals and incentives that they received from respective city and state governments are still valid post-election (https://www.businessinsider.com/amazon-to-announce-the-location-of-its-second-hq-by-the-end-of-2018-2018-9)

I am a resident of Atlanta who is also familiar with the tech scene. Atlanta's tech supply is not as good as it looks on paper, but it surpasses most other contenders. Atlanta's airport and transportation facilities are hands-down the best of all the candidates. (Note that UPS world headquarters is here.) Cost of living is low, while quality of life is close to all contenders except Denver (a no-go for the other reasons I list). Furthermore, the government of Georgia is aggressively pro-business with tax credits and other incentives...and, if I were Bezos, I'd realize I could seize de facto control of the city like Disney did with Orlando. Seattle is too wily for that, but the old boy network here isn't. Assuming these are relevant factors, I have a hard time understanding why they'd choose otherwise...and I'm no Atlanta booster.

However, there have been independent evals of the possible sites by third parties, including Moodys and the NYT. Moody's top 4 were Austin at #1, followed by ATL, PHI, and NYC. The NYT ranked the top three according to Amazon's criteria and had Denver as the top city, followed by Boston and DC. Plus, both Denver and Austin are already hubs for startups, which could be a plus, but I think that Amazon would rather pick a city that it could define. Peering into the mind of Jeff Bezos, I suspect that he has an interest in building a city around his empire, like the Chinese or Google are doing, and I don't think you could do that reliably in Austin, Denver, NYC, DC, Boston, or LA, unless you located Amazon on the outskirts.
